03593nam a22005895i 9780292767737DE-B159720211129102213.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211129t20211997txu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802927677377 a10.7560/7387062doi  a(DE-B1597)586769  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  atxucUS-TX 7aSOC0000002bisacsh04a306.9/09851 aIsbell, William H., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aMummies and Mortuary Monuments :bA Postprocessual Prehistory of Central Andean Social Organization /cWilliam H. Isbell. 1aAustin : bUniversity of Texas Press, c[2021] 4c©1997  a1 online resource (391 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tILLUSTRATIONS -- tAcknowledgments -- tCHAPTER I On Knowing the Past -- tCHAPTER II Royal Mummies of Inca Cuzco -- tCHAPTER III Ancestor Mummies in Huarochirí -- tCHAPTER IV Competing Theories of Ayllu Origins -- tCHAPTER V The Open Sepulcher -- tCHAPTER VI Distribution of Open Sepulcher Monuments -- tCHAPTER VII The Open Sepulchers of Chota-Cutervo -- tCHAPTER VIII Origin of the Ayllu and the Andean Past -- tBIBLIOGRAPHY -- tAUTHOR INDEX0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aSince prehistoric times, Andean societies have been organized around the ayllu, a grouping of real or ceremonial kinspeople who share labor, resources, and ritual obligations. Many Andean scholars believe that the ayllu is as ancient as Andean culture itself, possibly dating back as far as 6000 B.C., and that it arose to alleviate the hardships of farming in the mountainous Andean environment. In this boldly revisionist book, however, William Isbell persuasively argues that the ayllu developed during the latter half of the Early Intermediate Period (around A.D. 200) as a means of resistance to the process of state formation. Drawing on archaeological evidence, as well as records of Inca life taken from the chroniclers, Isbell asserts that prehistoric ayllus were organized around the veneration of deceased ancestors, whose mummified bodies were housed in open sepulchers, or challups, where they could be visited by descendants seeking approval and favors. By charting the temporal and spatial distribution of chullpa ruins, Isbell offers a convincing new explanation of where, when, and why the ayllu developed.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.7560/73870640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780292767737423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780292767737/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK